The decay \(\pi^+ ightarrow \mu^+ + 
u\) (with neutrino mass \(\approx 0\)) conserves energy and momentum. For a stationary pion, the total energy is \(m_{\pi} = 139.6\ 	ext{MeV}\). Let \(p\) be the magnitude of momentum of each product. Then \[ E_{\mu} = \sqrt{p^2 + m_{\mu}^2}, \quad E_{
u} = p. \] Energy conservation: \(E_{\mu} + p = m_{\pi}\). Solving gives \[ p =  rac{m_{\pi}^2 - m_{\mu}^2}{2 m_{\pi}}, \quad E_{\mu} =  rac{m_{\pi}^2 + m_{\mu}^2}{2 m_{\pi}}. \] With \(m_{\pi} = 139.6\ 	ext{MeV}\) and \(m_{\mu} = 105.7\ 	ext{MeV}\): \[ m_{\pi}^2 - m_{\mu}^2 = (139.6)^2 - (105.7)^2 = 19488.16 - 11172.49 = 8315.67\ 	ext{MeV}^2, \] \[ p =  rac{8315.67}{2 	imes 139.6} =  rac{8315.67}{279.2} \approx 29.78\ 	ext{MeV}. \] Thus \(T_{
u} = p \approx 29.8\ 	ext{MeV}\). \[ E_{\mu} = m_{\pi} - p \approx 139.6 - 29.78 = 109.82\ 	ext{MeV}, \] \[ T_{\mu} = E_{\mu} - m_{\mu} \approx 109.82 - 105.7 = 4.12\ 	ext{MeV}. \] These values match option C. ANSWER: C

